etention are under consideration by her Department.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","6246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388664","Home Office","false","2015-07-14","<p>The previous Government responded to the Council of Europe Experts on Action Against Trafficking in Human Beings recommendations on 11 March 2015. I will arrange to have a copy of the response placed in the House Library.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-07-14T16:05:36.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388664/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388664/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388664/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-08","Human Trafficking: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 26 February 2015 to Question 224996, if she will place in the Library a copy of the Government's response to the recommendations of the Council of Europe Experts on Action Against Trafficking Report.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","6153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388665","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-15","<p>The cargo ship Sunflower E was arrested by the Admiralty Marshal (an employee of Her Majesty’s Courts and Tribunals Service) pursuant to an arrest warrant issued in the Admiralty Court and is subject to ongoing court proceedings in the High Court. It has been under arrest since 10<sup>th</sup> March. I can confirm that the crew were repatriated on the 29 June by the International Transport Workers Federation. Whilst the crew were on board, the Admiralty Marshal ensured that they were provided with provision such as food, water and fuel throughout the period of detention of the vessel. The crew were free to leave the vessel at any point.</p><p>The vessel will remain under arrest until the vessel is sold or released by the Claimants.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-07-15T16:39:51.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388665/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388665/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-08","MV Sunflower E","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what representations he has received on the situation of the passengers of the cargo ship Sunflower E during its detention in Newport.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","6144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388666","Home Office","false","2015-08-27","<p>The Home Office subscribed to 117 journals during 2014 via a cross-government contract with a company called SwetsWise. Full year costs are not available because SwetsWise ceased trading in 2014, there may have been local arrangements in place, and it is not now possible to identify all the subscriptions in place during the course of the year. Subscriptions have not been centralised since that time. Compiling figures and details of local purchase arrangements as they stand at present for newspapers, periodicals and journals would only be possible at disproportionate cost.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-08-27T13:47:04.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388666/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388666/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388666/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388666/answer/previousversion/16617","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388666/answer/previousversion/16617","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388666/answer/previousversion/16617",,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-08","Home Office: Press","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which journals, periodicals and newspapers her Department subscribes to; how many copies of each such periodical and newspaper her Department receives each day; and what the cost of subscribing to such newspapers, journals and periodicals was in 2014.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","6128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388667","Home Office","false","2015-07-21","<p>Their deployment and use of police animals is an operational matter for chief constables. As such, the Home Office does not hold information on injures and deaths of police animals centrally. Any use of animals by the police must meet the welfare requirements of the Animal Welfare Act 2006.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-07-21T13:10:01.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388667/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388667/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388667/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-08","Police: Animals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) horses and (b) dogs have been (i) injured and (ii) killed while on police duty in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","6129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388668","Home Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Home Office does not hold the requested data centrally. The Home Office collects and publishes statistics on the police workforce at police force area level, but not at a lower geographical level.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-07-13T16:24:01.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388668/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388668/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388668/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-08","Police: Bradford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what changes there have been in the number of neighbourhood police officers in Bradford since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","6110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388669","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-15","<p>DFID is providing no financial assistance directly to the government of Burma. Our policy is that none of our bilateral aid is provided directly through central government systems, only through United Nations organisations, trusted international and local NGOs and, where circumstances allow, to authorities at the township level.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-07-15T13:29:20.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388669/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388669/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388669/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","Burma: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what conditions are attached to the financial aid her Department provides to Myanmar.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","6109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388670","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Government will make a capital contribution of $3.1bn (£2bn) to the Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank, to support much needed infrastructure investment in Asia and in turn increase global growth. Additional funding was provided at the Summer Budget for this financial transaction. This will not impact DfID existing budget. The current intention is that for 2015-16 this will be included in HM Treasury’s budget.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government will seek approval from Parliament for this contribution under Section 11 of the International Development Act.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-07-13T16:41:09.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388670/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388670/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388670/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-08","Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 7 July 2015 to Question 5228, how much of the UK's £2 billion capital contribution to the Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank is planned to be funded from the budget of the Department for International Development.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","6124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388671","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-13","<p>The UK is funding the Norwegian Refugee Council (NRC) to provide free legal support to Palestinian communities threatened with forced eviction, demolition and displacement and is also providing £1.1 million of technical assistance to support Palestinian villages at risk of demolition action to meet the requirements of the Israeli planning system. The UK will continue to raise concerns about demolitions and displacement with the Government of Israel on a regular basis and at the highest levels.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-07-13T16:29:51.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388671/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388671/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388671/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will take steps to support the residents of the village of Susiya in the West Bank in the event of the village being demolished.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","6132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388672","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-15","<p>Djibouti and Somalia have received most Yemeni refugees since the escalation of the conflict in Yemen in March 2015 based on available data. Humanitarian agencies report that approximately 9,583 Yemenis have fled to Djibouti and 2,113 have fled to Somalia. Data on the number of Yemenis who have fled to others countries in the Middle East is not yet available.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-07-15T13:27:30.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388672/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388672/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388672/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effect of the conflict in Yemen on the number of Yemeni refugees fleeing to other areas in the Middle East.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","6296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388673","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-16","<p>The Friends of Yemen group was established in 2010, with the UK, Saudi Arabia and Yemen as permanent co-chairs. The group reconvened in 2012, following the Arab Spring, to focus on providing political support to Yemen’s transition under the GCC Initiative and support for economic and security reform. The Friends of Yemen group last met in the margins of the UN General Assembly in September 2014. The UK remains committed to the objectives of the group, and the important co-ordination mechanism it offers. We will continue to encourage all parties to engage with UN-led political talks and do all that we can to improve the humanitarian situation.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-07-16T14:20:06.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388673/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388673/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-08","Friends of Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Government's Friends of Yemen group is active.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","6293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388674","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-13","<p>DFID and HM Treasury ministers and officials meet regularly to discuss issues of common interest, including tax and development. We have worked closely to progress the G20 agenda on tax and development to ensure that developing countries can participate in the G20/OECD Base Erosion and Profit Shifting (BEPS) process and are able to implement its outputs. At the Autumn Statement the Chancellor announced increased resources for the HMRC capacity building unit that I established in 2013, to recruit a dedicated team of experts to tackle tax avoidance and evasion in developing countries.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-07-13T16:33:09.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388674/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388674/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","Developing Countries: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with her Ministerial colleagues in HM Treasury on tax reform, helping developing countries to collect tax from multinational companies and the OECD Base Erosion and Profit Shifting process.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","6282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388675","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-15","<p>The World Bank suspended its operations and projects in Yemen in March 2015. More detailed information on the suspension can be found at: <a href="http://www.worldbank.org/en/news/press-release/2015/03/11/world-bank-suspends-operations-in-yemen" target="_blank">http://www.worldbank.org/en/news/press-release/2015/03/11/world-bank-suspends-operations-in-yemen</a></p><p> </p><p>As a result of the World Bank’s decision and the increase in conflict in Yemen, DFID suspended its “Yemen Mutual Accountability Framework” and “Building an Evidence Base “programmes with the World Bank. We are however continuing to work with the World Bank on a Country Economic Memorandum for Yemen which is nearing finalisation.</p><p> </p><p>More detailed information about all DFID-funded programmes in Yemen can be found at: <a href="http://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/countries/YE/" target="_blank">http://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/countries/YE/</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-07-15T13:48:28.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388675/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388675/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","Yemen: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department is continuing to take part in joint development programmes with the World Bank in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","6253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388676","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-15","<p>In March 2015, following the increase in conflict in Yemen, DFID suspended its “Support to Elections in Phase II of Yemen’s Transition&quot; programme, including the International Foundation for Electoral Systems’ activities. The programme formally ended on 31 May 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-07-15T13:46:34.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388676/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388676/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388676/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","Yemen: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department is continuing to take part in joint development programmes with the International Foundation for Electoral Systems in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","6251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388677","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-15","<p>DFID is continuing to fund Oxfam, CARE and Save the Children through the “Yemen Humanitarian Resilience Programme”, and Save the Children through the “Improving Nutrition in Yemen Programme” with UNICEF. Through these programmes, DFID is providing food, safe water, emergency livelihoods support, shelter and protection services, and helping to treat and prevent severe acute malnutrition.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>More detailed information about all DFID Yemen funded programmes can be found at: <a href="http://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/countries/YE/" target="_blank">http://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/countries/YE/</a>.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","6191 ; 6250","2015-07-15T13:45:46.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388677/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388677/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388677/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","Yemen: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department is continuing to take part in joint development programmes with Oxfam in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","6252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388678","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-15","<p>DFID is continuing to fund Oxfam, CARE and Save the Children through the “Yemen Humanitarian Resilience Programme”, and Save the Children through the “Improving Nutrition in Yemen Programme” with UNICEF. Through these programmes, DFID is providing food, safe water, emergency livelihoods support, shelter and protection services, and helping to treat and prevent severe acute malnutrition.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>More detailed information about all DFID Yemen funded programmes can be found at: <a href="http://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/countries/YE/" target="_blank">http://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/countries/YE/</a>.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","6191 ; 6252","2015-07-15T13:45:46.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388678/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388678/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","Yemen: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department is continuing to take part in joint development programmes with CARE in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","6250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388679","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-15","<p>I am proud of the leadership role that my Department has taken, and continues to take, in tackling violence against women and girls. The voices of women and girls were at the heart of Girl Summit 2014 and the Global Summit to End Sexual Violence in Conflict, and we are making significant progress towards ending FGM, child early and forced marriage and sexual violence in conflict across the world. My Department regularly consults with women’s rights organisations and women in developing countries to tackle violence against women and girls, including through global decision-making processes such as the Sustainable Global Goals.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-07-15T15:45:21.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388679/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388679/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388679/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","Developing Countries: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department has taken to ensure that the voices of women working in developing countries to tackle violence against women are heard in the global decision-making processes.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","6230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388680","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-14","<p>Supporting women’s rights organisations is vital to challenging harmful social norms and supporting collective action to bring about change. DFID supports women’s rights organisations through several Civil Society Organisations (CSOs) such as Womankind, Vital Voices and through the UN Trust Fund to end Violence against Women.</p><p> </p><p>In March I announced £8 million for AmplifyChange, an initiative which supports community based organisations to take action on a number of neglected sexual and reproductive health and rights (SRHR) and gender issues including child, early and forced marriage (CEFM), female genital mutilation (FGM) and violence against women and girls (VAWG).</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-07-14T15:11:53.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388680/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388680/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388680/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","Developing Countries: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department has taken to ensure that resources are reaching women working at the grassroots in developing countries defending women's rights.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","6231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388681","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-14","<p>As with many other areas of development work, the need to tackle underpinning social norms to address violence against women and girls means that many of our programmes are multi-year and complex, so it is very difficult to say precisely what the figure is each year. 90 programmes in our portfolio contain elements which address violence against women and girls directly, according to the mapping work undertaken by the consultancy Oxford Policy Management in August 2014. These include sectoral programmes working on education, health, security and justice and humanitarian response.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Funding for our 19 VAWG-focused programmes (those programmes where VAWG is the only issue addressed) increased significantly between 2012 and 2014, from just under £20 million in 2012 to £131 million in 2014. However, as this does not include the many programmes where VAWG is mainstreamed, the total figure spent on this area by my department will be significantly higher.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-07-14T15:15:08.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388681/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388681/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388681/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","Developing Countries: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what funding her Department has allocated to projects tackling violence against women and girls in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","6232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388682","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-13","<p>As a country that has met its commitment to spend 0.7% of GNI on international development, the UK’s priority for the UN Financing for Development Conference is to provide a solid foundation for the post-2015 summit in September and the climate meeting in December.</p><p> </p><p>The UK is seeking an innovative approach to development finance that helps developing countries mobilise their own tax revenues and catalyses private financial flows, building on the progress made at the 2013 UK-led G8 summit in the areas of trade, tax and transparency.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening","6268","2015-07-13T16:32:13.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388682/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388682/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388682/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","International Conference on Financing for Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what her priorities are for the forthcoming UN Financing for Development conference.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","6267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388683","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-13","<p>As a country that has met its commitment to spend 0.7% of GNI on international development, the UK’s priority for the UN Financing for Development Conference is to provide a solid foundation for the post-2015 summit in September and the climate meeting in December.</p><p> </p><p>The UK is seeking an innovative approach to development finance that helps developing countries mobilise their own tax revenues and catalyses private financial flows, building on the progress made at the 2013 UK-led G8 summit in the areas of trade, tax and transparency.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening","6267","2015-07-13T16:32:13.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388683/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388683/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388683/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","International Conference on Financing for Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what her priorities are for reforming taxation and private investment flows at the forthcoming UN Financing for Development conference.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","6268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388684","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-13","<p>The UK is funding the Norwegian Refugee Council (NRC) to provide free legal support to Palestinian communities threatened with forced eviction, demolition and displacement and is also providing £1.1 million of technical assistance to support Palestinian villages at risk of demolition action to meet the requirements of the Israeli planning system. The UK raises concerns about demolitions and displacement with the Government of Israel on a regular basis and at the highest levels. On 8 June, envoys from all 28 European Union Member States including the British Consul General to Jerusalem visited the Bedouin community at Susiya. The delegation’s visit was to emphasise their continuing support for the community and their opposition to demolitions in general.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-07-13T16:30:41.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388684/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388684/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388684/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent support her Department has provided to the residents of Susiya in the West Bank.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","6260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388685","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-13","<p>The UK provides assistance to communities in Area C through technical assistance and funding for the Norwegian Refugee Council (NRC) to provide free legal support to Palestinian communities threatened with forced eviction, demolition and displacement. We work closely with donor partners both through the EU and humanitarian agencies to prevent the forcible transfer of any Palestinian communities from Area C of the West Bank and to uphold International Humanitarian Law.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-07-13T16:31:26.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388685/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388685/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with donor partners about contingency planning for providing humanitarian assistance to the residents of Susiya in the West Bank in the event that that village is removed.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","6261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388686","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-15","<p>DFID’s responsibilities on climate and environment derive from the International Development Act’s commitment to sustainable development, based on the substantial evidence that poverty eradication is not possible without tackling climate change. Climate and environment risks and opportunities are considered as part of DFID’s programing to ensure it supports climate resilience and lower carbon growth to eradicate poverty. The capacity of DFID staff to do this has been developed through DFID’s ‘Future Fit’ programme which has worked with all DFID spending departments to develop climate plans.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition, the UK’s flagship International Climate Fund (ICF) has been used to integrate climate issues in DFID programmes in climate vulnerable sectors such as forestry, water, agriculture and disaster management. The ICF has already helped 15m people cope with the impacts of climate change, and created 39,000 jobs many of them in low carbon energy programmes that have provided access to low carbon energy to more than 2.8m people.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-07-15T15:31:42.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388686/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388686/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388686/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to ensure that all UK international aid is responsive to (a) climate change and (b) low carbon emissions; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","6196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388687","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-15","<p>DFID is continuing to fund Oxfam, CARE and Save the Children through the “Yemen Humanitarian Resilience Programme”, and Save the Children through the “Improving Nutrition in Yemen Programme” with UNICEF. Through these programmes, DFID is providing food, safe water, emergency livelihoods support, shelter and protection services, and helping to treat and prevent severe acute malnutrition.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>More detailed information about all DFID Yemen funded programmes can be found at: <a href="http://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/countries/YE/" target="_blank">http://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/countries/YE/</a>.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","6250 ; 6252","2015-07-15T13:45:45.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388687/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388687/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388687/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-08","Yemen: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department's joint development programmes with Save the Children in Yemen are active.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","6191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388688","Attorney General","false","2015-07-13","<p>In prosecuting cases of wilful neglect by social workers, prosecutors apply the two stages of the Full Code Test, as set out in the Code for Crown Prosecutors. There must be sufficient evidence for a realistic prospect of conviction and a prosecution must be in the public interest. The Director of Public Prosecutions will shortly issue further guidance for prosecutors on the ill treatment or wilful neglect offences created by sections 20 and 21 of the Criminal Justice and Courts Act 2015. These provisions allow for the prosecution of, amongst others, social workers and social care providers providing formal adult social care who ill-treat or wilfully neglect individuals in their care. They add to criminal offences addressing the ill-treatment or wilful neglect of children, adults who lack capacity, and those subject to the Mental Health Act 1983.</p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2015-07-13T10:34:06.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388688/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388688/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-07-08","Social Workers: Negligence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what the Government's policy is on the prosecution of social workers for wilful neglect.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","6149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388689","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-13","Since its inception, the Supreme Court has confirmed two declarations of incompatibility under section 4 of the Human Rights Act 1998, both of which had been made previously by the Court of Appeal. These were in the cases of R (F and Thompson) v SSHD (2010) UKSC 17 and T &amp; Anor, R (on the application of) v Secretary of State for the Home Department &amp; Anor [2014] UKSC 35.<p>In the first case, the incompatibility was remedied by the Sexual Offences Act 2003 (Remedial) Order 2012.</p><p> </p><p>In the second case, while the Government’s application to appeal to the Supreme Court was outstanding, changes were made to the Rehabilitation of Offenders Act 1974 (Exceptions) Order 1975 and to the Police Act 1997 by secondary legislation in response to the Court of Appeal’s earlier judgment.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2015-07-13T14:02:33.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388689/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388689/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-08","Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, on which occasions the Supreme Court has declared an incompatibility between domestic legislation and the European Convention on Human Rights under section 4 of the Human Rights Act 1998 since that Court's inception; and what the Government's response was in each such case.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","6204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388690","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-14","<p /> <p>This Government takes recovery and enforcement of financial impositions very seriously and remains committed to finding new ways to ensure impositions are paid and to trace those who do not pay. This is why there has been a year on year increase in the total amount of financial penalties collected over the last four years. The amount of money collected has risen from £259m to a record of £310 million at the end of 2014/15. This is an increase of £20m (7%) in cash collection of financial impositions (excluding confiscation) compared to that collected in 2013/14.</p><p> </p><p>The number of financial imposition accounts opened and closed since 2012 is published here: (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-court-statistics-quarterly-january-to-march-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-court-statistics-quarterly-january-to-march-2015</a>)</p><p> </p><p>Financial impositions include fines imposed in the Magistrates and Crown courts, costs orders, compensation orders, victim surcharge orders and unpaid fixed penalty notices and penalty notices for disorder which are registered as fines for enforcement.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-07-14T16:42:00.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388690/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388690/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-08","Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many fines have been (a) issued by courts and (b) collected in the most recent 12 months for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","6200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388691","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-16","<p>Visits are an important part of the rehabilitation of prisoners, allowing them to gain professional advice and support and enabling them to maintain family contact. Reasonable physical contact between a prisoner and a visitor should normally be permitted subject to any security considerations and public protection measures that may be in place.</p><p> </p><p>There are circumstances however in which closed visits may be imposed as a precautionary or preventative measure where necessary and proportionate in accordance with Prison Rule 34 (3) for reasons of securing good order and discipline, for the prevention of crime or in the interests of any individual. Each case must be considered on an individual basis and, where closed visits are imposed, subject to regular review. The tables below set out the number of young people who were placed on closed visits in each month for the last three years for which figures are available.</p><p> </p><p>2012</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>July</p></td><td><p>Aug</p></td><td><p>Sept</p></td><td><p>Oct</p></td><td><p>Nov</p></td><td><p>Dec</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cookham Wood</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Feltham</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Parc</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Warren Hill</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Werrington</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wetherby</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td>